                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote>
                        The manuscript was written in 1476 by a nun (see colophon, above) and decorated by the brothers <persName key="person_95822887" role="art">Gherardo del Fora</persName> and <persName key="person_95773817" role="art">Monte di Giovanni di Miniato del Fora</persName>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  
                  <decoDesc resp="#PA">
                     <summary><ref target="https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000468709">Pächt and Alexander</ref> ii. 306, Pl. XXVIII
                     </summary>
                     
                     <decoNote type="border">Fine historiated borders, e. g. <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/3d8c0e18-2e25-4c86-b657-9b9c5fb33ce6/">fol. 451v</ref></decoNote>
                     <decoNote type="decInit">Fine initials, e. g. <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/3d8c0e18-2e25-4c86-b657-9b9c5fb33ce6/">fol. 451v</ref>. 
                        Many small initials. The larger ones with borders include those on fol. 15r, fol. 216r, fol. 290c, fol. 416r, fol. 425v and fol. 489b</decoNote>
                     <decoNote>Fol. 216r: the beginning of the Psalms and framed by a border composed of foliage, flowers, rayed gold studs, putti and small miniatures. 
                        The miniature at the foot of the page represents David with Goliath's head, a smaller one on the righthand side depicts the bust of a prophet.
                        David is shown playing the harp within the initial <hi rend="bold">B</hi>
                        (Otto Pächt, <ref target="https://www.zotero.org/groups/434020/bodleian_library_western_medieval_manuscripts_bibliography/tags/MS.%20Canon.%20Liturg.%20168/items/I74K9ZXJ/item-list"><title>Italian Illuminated 
                           Manuscripts from 1400 to 1550</title></ref> [1948], p. 20)</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <bindingDesc resp="#BCBB">
                     <binding notAfter="1600" notBefore="1500">
                        <p>16th century?, <placeName key="place_1000080">Italian</placeName>: wood boards, inside bevel; light brown leather, blind-tooled with sextuple lines alternating with rows of one repeated stamp; 
                           spine with same blind tools and (later?) gilt title ‘BREVIARIVM’; remains of two strap-and-pin fastenings with darker leather straps, once running from front fore-edge to pins towards 
                           centre back, one strap still present in 1897 (since lost) and one pin with small square base still surviving; edges gilt, gauffered</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
